The Study 1 GWAS included 4 principal components (PCs) as covariates as well as sex and age. This selection was based on the scree plot in the R script. The amount of variance explained is almost zero once PC5 is reached, so only the first 4 were included in the analyses as the majority of variance can be explained by these PCs. The Study 2 GWAS included age, sex, and PCs 1-4 as covariates.

After EasyQC filtering, GWAS 1 included 451,832 variants while GWAS 2 included 454,154 variants.

According to the EasyQC report, GWAS1 dropped 17 variants and GWAS2 dropped 14. All dropped variants in both studies were excluded because they were duplicates. There were 68 variants flagged as outliers during the allele frequency check in GWAS1. There were 71 variants flagged as outliers during the allele frequency check in GWAS2. There were 29 variants in each study that were flagged for an invalid reference allele.

Given that our phenotype of interest is quantitative (not case/control), a conservative minor allele count threshold of 6 has been applied to both studies where any SNPs with an MAC of 6 or more have been retained. Additionally, any SNPs that had missing genotype calls for 30 or more samples were excluded (N >= 1,247 and 1,196 for study 1 and 2, respectively). After filtering by these thresholds, GWAS1 has retained 451,085 SNPs (747 excluded) and GWAS2 has 453,453 SNPs (701 excluded).

After filtering both studies by a MAC threshold of 6 and an N of 30, neither the Manhattan nor the qq plots seem to have changed much. Additionally, the lambda values for both the filtered and unfiltered studies are nearly identical. Given that, and the fact that neither lambda is greater than 1.1, there is no indication of inflation in either study.

The same MAC and sample size filters were applied to the meta analysis data as well. The plots were re-drawn and lambda recalculated as shown below.

# thresholds
summary(meta_analysis$Weight)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1165    2503    2503    2393    2503    2503
# merge in mac
meta_temp_2 <- study_1_GWAS[,c(2,11)] %>% rename(MarkerName = SNP)
meta_analysis <- left_join(meta_analysis,meta_temp_2, by.x=MarkerName, by.y=MarkerName)

meta_filtered <- meta_analysis %>% filter(MAC >= 6 & Weight >= 2473)

# new plots
meta_man_filt <- manhattan(meta_filtered, chr="chr", snp="MarkerName", p="pval", bp = "bp", main = "Meta-Analysis Filtered Manhattan", annotatePval = 1e-40, annotateTop = FALSE)

# meta qq
meta_qq_filt <- qq(meta_filtered$pval, main = "Meta-Analysis Filtered QQ Plot")

# meta lambda
## create p value vector
meta_p_filt <- as.vector(meta_filtered$pval)
## calculate lambda
meta_lam_filt <- median(qchisq(1-meta_p_filt,1))/qchisq(0.5,1)

After filtering the meta analysis data by the same thresholds for MAC and N, both the Manhattan and QQ plots look almost identical as prior to filtering. Additionally, the lambda values are nearly identical pre- and post- filtering. This indicates that there is likely no inflation happening and any associations observed are due to true association.

With the filters set above, the strongest associated SNP was determined.

The strongest association in the meta analysis is SNP rs26540 with a p value of 2.18e-188. This SNP is located on chromosome 5 at basepair position 111,349,320. In GWAS study 1, this SNP had a p value of 4.208e-93 with an effect size of 4.11. In GWAS study 2, this SNP had a p value of 2.308e-97 with an effect size of 4.253. Both individual studies and the meta analysis are consistent in positive effect direction for this SNP.
